2":"1382","1292":"1292","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kelshall, Hertfordshire, England":"Kelshall, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"1315–":"1315–Overleden","1315–Male":"1315–Overleden","1240–Female":"1240–Overleden","1342–Male":"1342–Overleden","1287–Male":"1287–Overleden","1292–Female":"1292–Overleden","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1342":"1342","1287":"1287","1340":"1340","1240":"1240","1382":"1382","1292":"1292","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kelshall, Hertfordshire, England":"Kelshall, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1315–":"1315–Deceased","1315–Male":"1315–Deceased","1240–Female":"1240–Deceased","1342–Male":"1342–Deceased","1287–Male":"1287–Deceased","1292–Female":"1292–Deceased","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1342":"1342","1287":"1287","1340":"1340","1240":"1240","1382":"1382","1292":"1292","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kelshall, Hertfordshire, England":"Kelshall, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Barry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donal, Aidan, Ciaran, Eoin, John Patrick, Kaitlin, Kieran, Murphy, Aileen, Brigid, Caitlin.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Beargha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beargh</i>’, a byname meaning ‘plunderer’.","Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Báire</b> ‘descendant of <i>Báire</i>’, a short form of either of two Gaelic personal names, <i>Bairrfhionn</i> or <i>Fionnbharr</i>, both meaning ‘fair-topped’. This may also be the source of the Manx name <i>Barry</i>, whose family's main seat was Ballavarry in Kirk Andreas."],"variants":[{"name":"Barr","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow) and northern Irish (Ulster): habitational name from any of various places in southwestern Scotland, in particular Ayrshire and Renfrewshire, named with Gaelic <i>barr</i> ‘height, hill’ or a Brittonic cognate of this.","English and Welsh: habitational name from Great Barr in Staffordshire. This is from Brittonic <i>barro-</i> ‘top, summit’, referring to Barr Beacon; there is evidence that this was known as <i>la Bare</i> in the 13th century.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Barre-en-Ouche in Eure, France, or perhaps from Barre-de-Semilly in Manche, France."]},{"name":"Barrie","meanings":["Scottish (Angus): habitational name from Barry in Angus or from another place so named, generally named with Gaelic <i>barr</i> ‘height, hill’, or from a British cognate of this word. This name is also the Scottish form of   Barry  .","French (<b>Barrié</b>): variant of   Barrier  .","Altered form of French   Baril  . Compare   Barry   7."]},{"name":"Berry","meanings":["Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Béara</b> ‘descendant of <i>Béara</i>’, a personal name of unexplained etymology; or, in some cases, perhaps an Anglicized form of Irish and Manx <b>Ó Beargha</b>. Compare   Barry   1.","Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Barrie  .","English: habitational name from any of several places called in Devon named with Old English <i>byrig</i>, dative case of <i>burh</i> ‘fortified manor house, stronghold’, such as Berry Pomeroy and Berrynarbor."]},{"name":"Dubarry","meanings":["French: variant of the topographic or habitational name   Barry  , with fused preposition and definite article <i>du</i> ‘from the’."]},{"name":"Baril","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Normand, Alain, Armand, Ghislaine, Jacques, Jean-Marc, Jean-Pierre, Lucien, Monique, Phillippe.","French: from Old French <i>baril</i> ‘barrel’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for a cooper, or a nickname for a rotund man. Compare   Barry   7 and   Berry   7.","History: Jean Baril from the Saintonge region of France was in QC by 1673, when he married Marie Guillet, the first of his three wives. He died in 1724 in Batiscan, QC. His descendants also bear altered forms of the surname, such as <i>Barrie</i>, <i>Bar(r)y</i>, and <i>Berry</i>."]},{"name":"Bary","meanings":["Walloon and northern French: variant of   Barry   8.","French (southern): rare variant of   Barry   6.","Altered form of French   Baril  . Compare   Barry   7."]}]},{"name":"Osmond","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["19th-century revival of an Old English personal name composed of <i>ōs</i> ‘god’ + <i>mund</i> ‘protector’. The name was also in use among the Normans and was borne by an 11th-century saint who was appointed to the see of Salisbury by  William  the Conqueror. As a modern given name it may be in part a transferred use of the surname derived from this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Osmund","meanings":["Some translate this name 'house-peace.' \nWachter renders it 'excellent, gallant, brave man'"]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":0,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":13,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705195,"age":67,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Osmond Barry was born in 1315, in England, his father, Hugh Berry, was 28 and his mother, Cecily de Hemgrave, was 23. He married Alice Mikelfelde in 1340, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in his hometown, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1315–":"1315–Surnud","1315–Male":"1315–Surnud","1240–Female":"1240–Surnud","1342–Male":"1342–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1342":"1342","1287":"1287","1340":"1340","1240":"1240","1382":"1382","1292":"1292","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kelshall, Hertfordshire, England":"Kelshall, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1315–":"1315–Kuollut","1315–Male":"1315–Kuollut","1240–Female":"1240–Kuollut","1342–Male":"1342–Kuollut","1287–Male":"1287–Kuollut","1292–Female":"1292–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1342":"1342","1287":"1287","1340":"1340","1240":"1240","1382":"1382","1292":"1292","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kelshall, Hertfordshire, England":"Kelshall, Hertfordshire, England","England":"England","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1315–":"1315–Décédé","1315–Male":"1315–Décédé","1240–Female":"1240–Décédée","1342–Male":"1342–Décédé","1287–Male":"1287–Décédé","1292–Female":"1292–Décédée","1315":"1315","1312":"1312","1342":"1342","1287":"1287","1340":"1340","1240":"1240","1382":"1382","1292":"1292","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Kelshall, Hertfordshire, England":"Kelshall, Hertfordshire, Angleterre","England":"Angleterre","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Osmond Barry est né en 1315, à Angleterre, son père, Hugh Berry, avait 28 ans et sa mère, Cecily de Hemgrave, avait 23 ans. Il a épousé Alice Mikelfelde en 1340, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins